  "prompt": "Is it generally understood that money laundering is illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, it is **widely and generally understood** that **money laundering** is **illegal**. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or organized crime) to make it appear as if it came from legitimate sources. This process is criminalized in most jurisdictions worldwide because it enables further illegal activity, undermines financial systems, and fosters economic instability.\n\nLaws against money laundering exist in nearly every country, often as part of broader anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks. These laws typically impose severe penalties, including substantial fines and imprisonment. Additionally, international organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to set global standards and promote measures to combat money laundering.\n\nSo, yes, money laundering is universally recognized as illegal, and those involved in such activities can face serious legal consequences.",
